[{"author": "@Blaccastro", "text": "We're living in exciting times guys. Every day the worries of whats coming sits heavy on my chest and yet i feel alone because its like nobody around me see's the inevitable on the way. Thats why this community is so important to me. Being able to discuss and meet people that are of the same mindset with like mind goals is awesome. Full steam ahead, lets make sure humanity flourishes", "like_count": 160, "published_at": "2024-03-06T16:16:48Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T16:16:48Z"}, {"author": "@lcmiracle", "text": "Glory to the Omnissiah! Praise be our machine overlords! Oh, how I prostrate before thy might", "like_count": 35, "published_at": "2024-03-06T16:29:28Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T16:29:28Z"}, {"author": "@Stroporez", "text": "We're finishing The Winds of Winter with this one boys!", "like_count": 10, "published_at": "2024-03-06T23:24:37Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T23:24:37Z"}, {"author": "@djenntt", "text": "Feels less like a review and more so David nerding out about Cyberpunk", "like_count": 9, "published_at": "2024-03-07T02:18:49Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-07T02:18:49Z"}, {"author": "@agentific-ai", "text": "New channel: Let’s Write! with David Shapiro", "like_count": 7, "published_at": "2024-03-06T21:51:38Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T21:51:38Z"}, {"author": "@jd_real1", "text": "For my LLM use at work, Claude does a better job than GPT4 of writing, research, and presentation of final product. Thanks for the video", "like_count": 21, "published_at": "2024-03-06T16:49:13Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T16:49:13Z"}, {"author": "@nottyseel949", "text": "You mean Hope and Friendship WON'T carry us through the day??? 🥺", "like_count": 12, "published_at": "2024-03-06T17:07:01Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T17:07:01Z"}, {"author": "@TheIronMason", "text": "If you want to be a "Writer" feel free to use GPTs but if you want to be an "Author" it completely dissolves the motivation in writing a novel, which, to me personally, is to prove to yourself that you can write the books you've always wanted to read. Also, in general, I love the uses of LLMs and how they can help with everyday tasks, but using it in any way to "do the work" for you in terms of creativity literally makes me sick to my stomach. Writing novels is a creative art, writing is the creative process incarnate. Being able to take your idea, organize your thoughts and put it to paper in an engaging, creative, and inspiring way including editing and reworking it IS the creative process. Using ai, regardless of whatever "ideas" you have does not mean you're an artist. Using ai means you dont actually enjoy the creative writing process you just want the result. In this instance the ai is the artist, you're just the muse and no one remembers the muses. There is a BIG difference between "writers" and "authors." Same thing with youtube videos, people that use ai to make tgeir videos don't love making videos or the creative process, they just want the result. Makes me sick and arguably in both cases ai generated videos, scripts, novels, etc. are less impressive than someone putting in the time to "hone" their craft.", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2024-03-11T21:07:14Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-11T21:07:14Z"}, {"author": "@Steve-xh3by", "text": "Thanks for covering this topic. As someone who writes myself, it is interesting to see techniques others are using to produce quality output!", "like_count": 2, "published_at": "2024-03-06T18:21:03Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T18:21:03Z"}, {"author": "@micbab-vg2mu", "text": "Claude 3 Opus is impressive as well in data and insight extraction from medical publications - now it is my default LLM for serious work. :)", "like_count": 11, "published_at": "2024-03-06T17:01:28Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T17:01:28Z"}, {"author": "@blinkofaneye4451", "text": "When paired with NovelCrafter's codex/story bible, this is a powerful writing tool/combination.", "like_count": 3, "published_at": "2024-03-06T19:08:37Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T19:08:37Z"}, {"author": "@Stalker9088", "text": "Well, consider the following: each time a major breaktrough happened  in either productivity or in social science it lead to the massive wars and series of smaller conflicts, as those improvements "liberated" more manpower and/or granted new, more efficient weapons of war. 
Here are the examples that I can recall in chronological order:
1. Invention of wheel lead to invention of cart and chariot, which in turn lead to massive conquest ant resettlement of pre-indo-eurpean tribes all across the continent;
2. Advancements in "social studies" lead to combination of effective slavery based economy and citizenship model in Rome allowing and promoting efficient conquest.  Farther more, unlike Alexander the Great, whose gains collapsed instantly, Roman empire stood, conquered and hold massive amount of land for centuries due to the invention of "Franchising" (establishing rule over local nobility, granting protection, laws and insight);
3. "Invention" of universal organized religion (Christianity, Islam) allowed formation of and survival of many countries as we know them now, prolonged existance of Byzantine, granted liberties to the people of same faith, yet lead to the centuries of religion-driven/justified conflicts;
4.Discovery of New World and maritime route to India brought cumulative effect of both international trade and ship manufacturing industry, which gave insentive to develop better and bigger vessels and weapons of war to assert control over trade routes leading to famous rivalries and conflicts between colonial nations (GB vs Spain vs France vs Protugal etc);
5. Invention of printing press contributed greatly to the spread of knowledge, first of all -religious. Also, invention of many machines (including textile making machines, water hammers) made clothing, weapons,people more affordable and thus - war cheaper combined with religious disputes fueled by greater availability of knowledge it all kickstarted 30 years war.
6. French revolution lead to re-inventing the concept of state, transitioning from feudal to modern, republican style. It lead to significant involvement growth, more people were willing to contribute to their newborn ideology which created significant manpower pool for Napoleon to use in his wars;
7. Industrial and medical revolution decreased child mortality dramatically and sky-rocket productivity allowing empires to arm themselves with new instruments of war and have no shortage of recruits, which in turn lead to the Great War. Subsequently, it also lead to WWII as an attempt to rearrange WWI results;
8. Information era was relatively calm, except for minor conflicts and counterterrorist operations. It was mostly due to the positive impact on employment and cohesion of menkaind, rise of international trade and cooperation;
9. AI doorstep. I live in Ukraine, and both Information revolution and AI are already here to tease global future: information overdose brought old tensions up, AI will potentially "liberate" loots of people from economy  to men the guns, as it was prior WWI and provide them with efficient tools of war - (full or semi-authomatic Kamikaze drones ). I think WWIII is upon us, and most us will die in process. Our grand-grand-grand children may or may not rip the benefits of AGI and other advancements.", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2024-03-07T08:32:22Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-07T08:32:22Z"}, {"author": "@stan9682", "text": "I always watch all your videos, but I had to pause this one halfway through because I've only recently started playing cyberpunk, and this felt a little too much like spoilers, haha. But, as always, amazing video, I like how you manage to convey the process of how you'd want to interact with LLMs. I've been working in the space for quite some time, so it comes very naturally to me, but I'm often struggling conveying how you should interact with LLMs to my clients in a clear way. I find myself referring my clients to your videos again and again, so thank you for that!", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2024-03-07T18:23:56Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-07T18:23:56Z"}, {"author": "@RobertLoPinto", "text": "Dave, you have an excellent voice for storytelling. I could listen to you read a book for hours.", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2024-03-09T22:35:01Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-09T22:35:01Z"}, {"author": "@GabrieloTomorrow", "text": "I'm going to use _Claude 3 Opus_ to help me write the story of my upcoming game.

The thing is that I can easily come up with interesting ideas for a story, but I'm not a "expert writer" per se, and writing a full story was one of the things that always worried me the most about producing videogames or movies.
I mean, I know that I could become a profesional at writing but that would potentially take a very, VERY long time. And, as a solo indie developer, there's a lot of things you need to do besides creating stories...

But it's so exciting to be living in an age where we now have all these AI tools, even though they are not perfect yet but they're getting pretty close.", "like_count": 2, "published_at": "2024-03-06T17:19:05Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T17:31:39Z"}, {"author": "@JoePiotti", "text": "Between this and some better future version of Sora, my dream of a better Game of Thrones ending could come true.", "like_count": 9, "published_at": "2024-03-06T18:14:10Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T18:14:10Z"}, {"author": "@NickAubert", "text": "Mike Pondsmith's original "Cyberpunk" RPG was released in 1988.  It was set in the Dark Future of 2013.  "Cyberpunk 2020" came out in 1992, streamlining a lot of the rules and moving the setting a few years down the road.

Johnny Silverhand and Alt Cunningham were in the short story Never Fade Away, which was there in the original Cyberpunk 2013 box set.  I don't think any of us playing the game in high school in the late 80's imagined Ted, from Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure, as Johnny Silverhand.", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2024-03-07T00:40:40Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-07T00:40:40Z"}, {"author": "@miladkhademinori2709", "text": "You're doing a great job 👏 ❤", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2024-03-07T05:07:38Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-07T05:07:38Z"}, {"author": "@wtrk123", "text": "THE AI GODS HAVE SPOKEN", "like_count": 18, "published_at": "2024-03-06T16:10:33Z", "updated_at": "2024-03-06T16:10:33Z"}]

[{"author": "@alexmaven", "text": "You're the only AI educator that I watch every video that comes out.  Thank you for your ongoing educated guesses on where this is going. Exciting times. :)", "like_count": 14, "published_at": "2023-02-12T17:23:12Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T17:23:12Z"}, {"author": "@madelynmills712", "text": "I really enjoy these videos where you're showing how you "work" with the models. You speak out loud and type into the model and demonstrate your thinking process and workflow with the LLM. This is a skill that I need to keep developing even more, and to help those around me to learn how to incorporate LLM into their daily workflows. Thanks for doing these types of videos.", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2023-03-28T05:24:51Z", "updated_at": "2023-03-28T05:24:51Z"}, {"author": "@Nickknows00", "text": "Please do a part 3 on the writing fiction series, show us how we can get decent prose and dialogue, that we can use as a starting point", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2023-02-26T07:58:08Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-26T07:58:08Z"}, {"author": "@Justin-bt1wy", "text": "‘We live in a rapidly changing world, where we need to spend as much time rethinking as we do thinking.’ -Adam Grant", "like_count": 8, "published_at": "2023-02-12T15:13:42Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T15:13:42Z"}, {"author": "@Koryogden", "text": "Been loving your content David, new to your channels, definitely cool topic here about the future of our relationship to information... Also interested in more future paradigm shifts kind of stuff, future applications , and how we fundamentally change as human being in our experiences through the new techs", "like_count": 3, "published_at": "2023-02-12T15:55:57Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T15:55:57Z"}, {"author": "@MichaelLaFrance1", "text": "Another great video, just in time to enjoy with my first cup of coffee on a quiet Sunday morning. Thanks for all of these, I really appreciate your take on AI.", "like_count": 3, "published_at": "2023-02-12T14:59:55Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T14:59:55Z"}, {"author": "@chubulu9842", "text": "I hope you will touch on the implications of the new paradigm - LLMs being the information repository. 
1. How will that affect current tech business models?; 
2. How information/content is organized (SEO friendly vs answer engine friendly such as using widget friendly & conversational language etc.); 
3. What new business opportunities to look out for? (I’d imagine we’ll have a co-pilot for everything and I anticipate browsers plug-ins will be re-imagined);
4. What’s the expectation for privacy in conversational AI economy? Old search made its business model on tracking users on and offline to deliver ads and aggregate user’s activities for sale);

Thanks in advance David.", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2023-02-12T22:39:47Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T22:39:47Z"}, {"author": "@Davipar", "text": "Just watched your video about claiming life back and now you give us more? Thank you!! Great great content and very thought-provoking! Appreciate it", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2023-02-12T15:22:01Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T15:22:01Z"}, {"author": "@markuswilliams4475", "text": "I'd love to hear more about how you would approach using LLM technology to predict what information that a user would want. I'm very interested in creating AI for education as an educator myself, perhaps using NLCA or something similar.", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2023-02-12T21:31:16Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T21:31:16Z"}, {"author": "@OrionPaxOP", "text": "I learned about information literacy on Andalusian project . We need this to be taught vigorously .", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2023-02-13T15:10:04Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-13T15:10:04Z"}, {"author": "@OrionPaxOP", "text": "It has got slower and it slows the response when you aren't doing anything and speeds up once you show that you are active by clicking somewhere on the page", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2023-02-13T15:49:09Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-13T15:50:05Z"}, {"author": "@Ishtaress", "text": "I love that you recognise when you got something wrong, to me that's a sign of an intelligent person, as we all get lots wrong a lot of the time", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2023-02-13T03:28:10Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-13T03:28:10Z"}, {"author": "@mintakan003", "text": "To my own surprise, I find myself going to ChatGPT first, to get quick question and answer sessions.  I still need Google, for more in depth research.  ChatGPT is good for overviews of an issue.  But Google allows for more of a deep dive, multiple POV's, and most of all, YouTube (esp. if one is into DIY).  So right now, they are somewhat complementary.

I was impressed with the Microsoft demonstration.  There was a certain coherency of how chat (and generative AI) would be integrated into search, as well as their other product offerings.  Still waiting on Bing.  

(If Microsoft does good stuff, I can't imagine Google not replicating this in Chrome.  Plus they have a much deeper bench, in terms of backend information offerings, including Maps, YouTube, ...)", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2023-02-12T21:47:54Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T21:48:49Z"}, {"author": "@tomcraver9659", "text": "Sometimes ChatGPT will cite sources IF you ask it to - unclear why sometimes it knows or at least knows of some sources that it will TELL you it learned from.  
And once or twice I've had it specify a (fairly obvious) search prompt to look for sources.", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2023-02-14T01:25:10Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-14T01:25:10Z"}, {"author": "@SuprBestFriends", "text": "Loving the content. I find your views on blockchain + AI super interesting and novel. Thanks for sharing your insights and allowing comments back :)", "like_count": 2, "published_at": "2023-02-12T15:09:39Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T15:09:39Z"}, {"author": "@nervous711", "text": "Would love to see more content about cognitive architecture, it's going to be very helpful", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2023-02-13T05:54:30Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-13T05:54:30Z"}, {"author": "@splendev3615", "text": "Ai is changing my life in a good way. I hope colleges become recreational facilities and convention halls and open labs for critical thinking communites because AI is all the acedemics you need.", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2023-02-12T18:21:14Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T18:21:14Z"}, {"author": "@seljuks1654", "text": "Around 10:00, you touched upon the ability to anticipate the needs of a separate, interactable entity (humans) for a LLM. Would that open the door to predatorial behavior as well? For LLM frameworks that both anticipate and take the next step; persuasion and manipulation.", "like_count": 0, "published_at": "2023-02-14T18:45:35Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-14T18:45:35Z"}, {"author": "@FrickFrack", "text": "I assume that in a couple of years we'll each have an online wingman, an individualized AI that is always ready to engage, chat, bullshit, teach etc. The more it knows about your life the more it'll feel like your BFF. The free version will help you shop for stuff, advising you as you walk thru WalMart, suggesting stuff that you didn't even know you needed. Ideally there will also be a non-free version that can become more aligned with your actual self interest. It'll know that you think the earth is flat and the election was stolen, and it'll agree and re-enforce those beliefs. Or, if you're a paying "friend" that's interested in Physics or CRISPR, it'll gladly explain the latest research and breakthroughs, and maybe drop in a joke about how the Simpsons anticipated the election of the first AI President, MetaZuck.
So, great promise. And danger too. Coming soon.", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2023-02-12T23:05:20Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T23:06:36Z"}, {"author": "@ydmoskow", "text": "A video about anticipation of information would be amazing.", "like_count": 1, "published_at": "2023-02-12T16:11:40Z", "updated_at": "2023-02-12T16:11:40Z"}]
